<subSubSection pageId="107" pageNumber="108" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">
75. 
<taxonomicName LSID="EB728125-BE96-566A-BA35-EED02F68EC3B" authority="Rech. f., Biol. Skr. 10 (3): 81. 1959. (Rechinger 1959: 81)." authorityName="Rech. f., Biol. Skr. 10 (3): 81. 1959. (Rechinger" authorityYear="1959" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus rectangularis" order="Solanales" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rectangularis">Convolvulus rectangularis Rech.f., Biol. Skr. 10(3): 81. 1959. (Rechinger 1959: 81).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="107" pageNumber="108" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">
AFGHANISTAN, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Volk</emphasis>
1018 (holotype W!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="107" pageNumber="108" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">
Perennial herb with woody rootstock from which arise many wiry, probably scrambling stems to at least 25 cm; stems striate, glabrescent. Leaves very shortly petiolate, 1-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-0.6 cm, lanceolate-deltoid, acute, margin entire to sinuate-lobed, base truncate to auriculate, shortly crisped pubescent when young, glabrescent; petioles 1-3 mm. Flowers 1-3, borne on axillary peduncles; peduncles 1-1.5 cm; bracteoles 2.5 mm, filiform; pedicels 4-10 mm; outer sepals 9-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
6 mm, broadly oblong-rectangular, truncate and minutely mucronate, margin scarious, purplish, pubescent and with ciliate margins, inner sepals oblong, c. 4 mm wide; corolla 2.3-3.2 cm long, pinkish, midpetaline bands pubescent; filaments glandular below; ovary glabrous, style glabrous, divided c. 7 mm above base; stigmas not seen. Capsule glabrous; seeds wrinkled. [
<bibRefCitation author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 104; 
<bibRefCitation author="Rechinger, KH" editor="Rechinger, KH" journalOrPublisher="Akademische Druck und Verlagsanstalt, Graz" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 24" refId="B298" refString="Rechinger, KH, 1963. Convolvulaceae. In: Rechinger, KH, Ed., Flora Iranica. Akademische Druck und Verlagsanstalt, Graz: 1 - 24" title="Convolvulaceae." volumeTitle="Flora Iranica." year="1963">Rechinger 1963</bibRefCitation>
: 17]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="107" pageNumber="108" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">
Afghanistan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Rechinger</emphasis>
35902, 37103).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="107" pageNumber="108" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="107" pageNumber="108">
Although placed as distantly related in different sections by 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rech. f., Biol. Skr. 10 (3): 81. 1959. (Rechinger" authorityYear="1959" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus rectangularis" order="Solanales" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rectangularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Convolvulus rectangularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus lanjowii" order="Solanales" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanjowii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Convolvulus lanjowii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are quite close and might prove to be conspecific. The description above is based on the two widely distributed Rechinger collections cited above. These differ clearly in their sparse indumentum and in the sinuate-lobed narrower leaves with a rather rigid texture from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sa'ad, Meded. Bot. Mus. Herb. Rijks Univ. Utrecht 281: 232. 1967. (Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus lanjouwii" order="Solanales" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanjouwii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Convolvulus lanjouwii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However the type and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Amsel</emphasis>
s.n. (W) are much more hirsute and with unlobed leaves so approaching 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sa'ad, Meded. Bot. Mus. Herb. Rijks Univ. Utrecht 281: 232. 1967. (Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus lanjouwii" order="Solanales" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lanjouwii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="107" pageNumber="108">Convolvulus lanjouwii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Further collections are needed to confirm whether two distinct species are really involved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
